# Fast & Slow Pointers (Floyd's Algorithm)

Two pointers traverse the same structure at **different speeds** — slow moves 1 step, fast moves 2. Their relative motion reveals structure without any extra memory.

### The two superpowers
**1. Cycle detection.** If there's a loop, the fast pointer eventually laps the slow one. Inside the cycle the gap shrinks by exactly 1 per step, so they MUST meet. No cycle → fast hits `null`.

**2. Finding the middle.** When fast reaches the end, slow is exactly halfway.

### The template
```javascript
let slow = head, fast = head;
while (fast && fast.next) {
  slow = slow.next;
  fast = fast.next.next;
  if (slow === fast) return true; // cycle!
}
return false;
```

### Why interviewers love it
The obvious solution (a visited `Set`) costs O(n) memory. Fast & slow does it in **O(1) space** — mentioning both and explaining the trade-off is an instant signal.

**Classic problems:** Linked List Cycle I & II · Middle of the Linked List · Happy Number · Find the Duplicate Number · Palindrome Linked List

# Monotonic Stack

A stack that stays **sorted** (say, increasing bottom→top) by popping every element that would break the order before pushing. The moment an element gets popped, you've learned something: the incoming element is its **next greater element**.

### How to recognize it
- "**Next greater** / next smaller element…"
- "How many days until a warmer temperature?"
- "Largest rectangle…" — anything about the nearest element that dominates

### The template
```javascript
const stack = []; // indexes
for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
  while (stack.length && nums[stack.at(-1)] < nums[i]) {
    const j = stack.pop();
    answer[j] = nums[i]; // nums[i] is j's next greater!
  }
  stack.push(i);
}
```

### The complexity magic
It looks like O(n²) — a loop in a loop. But each element is pushed **once** and popped **at most once**, so the total work is O(n). Say this in the interview; it's the point of the question.

**Classic problems:** Next Greater Element I/II · Daily Temperatures · Largest Rectangle in Histogram · Remove K Digits

