# Merge Intervals

Problems about **ranges on a line** — meetings, bookings, IP blocks. The universal first move: **sort by start**. After sorting, overlap detection needs only ONE comparison per interval.

### The key insight
After sorting, interval `b` overlaps the current merged block iff `b.start <= block.end`. Nothing earlier can surprise you — that's what sorting bought.

### The template
```javascript
intervals.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0]);
const merged = [];
for (const [s, e] of intervals) {
  const last = merged[merged.length - 1];
  if (last && s <= last[1]) {
    last[1] = Math.max(last[1], e); // overlap → extend
  } else {
    merged.push([s, e]);            // gap → new block
  }
}
```

### Watch out
- `last[1] = Math.max(last[1], e)` — NOT just `e`. `[1,10]` followed by `[2,3]` must stay `[1,10]`.
- Decide whether touching intervals (`[1,3]`,`[3,5]`) count as overlapping — ask the interviewer!

**Complexity:** O(n log n) for the sort, O(n) for the sweep.

**Classic problems:** Merge Intervals · Insert Interval · Meeting Rooms I & II · Non-overlapping Intervals

