# Breadth-First Search

Explore a graph or grid **level by level** using a queue: everything at distance 1, then distance 2, and so on — like a wave. Because you visit nodes in distance order, **the first time BFS reaches a node is via a shortest path**.

### How to recognize it
- "**Shortest** path / **minimum** number of steps" in an **unweighted** graph, grid, or state space
- "How many islands / connected regions?"
- Word transformations, lock combinations — anything where states connect by single moves

### The template (grid version)
```javascript
const queue = [[startR, startC]];
const seen = new Set([`${startR},${startC}`]);
let dist = 0;
while (queue.length) {
  const levelSize = queue.length;       // process one ring
  for (let i = 0; i < levelSize; i++) {
    const [r, c] = queue.shift();
    if (isTarget(r, c)) return dist;
    for (const [nr, nc] of neighbors(r, c)) {
      if (valid(nr, nc) && !seen.has(`${nr},${nc}`)) {
        seen.add(`${nr},${nc}`);
        queue.push([nr, nc]);
      }
    }
  }
  dist++;
}
```

### The #1 bug
Marking nodes visited **when popped** instead of **when pushed** — the queue fills with duplicates. Mark on push.

**Complexity:** O(V + E) — every cell/node once.

**Classic problems:** Number of Islands · Rotting Oranges · Word Ladder · Shortest Path in Binary Matrix · 01 Matrix

